ThinkPart(
    type='think',
    think='This structure test was added by commit `85498d7` to ensure container
_name isn\'t hardcoded. And indeed, the current docker-compose.yml doesn\'t have
hardcoded container_names (they were removed in that commit).\n\nBut the E2E fai
lure wasn\'t about container name conflicts - it was about Docker network IP poo
l exhaustion. The network names are still based on the project name (directory n
ame), so each worktree creates a unique network.\n\nWait, looking at the docker-
compose.yml again:\n```yaml\nnetworks:\n  sw-network:\n    driver: bridge\n```\n
\nWhen docker-compose runs, it creates a network named `<project>_sw-network`. T
he project name defaults to the directory name. So each worktree creates `dev-is
sue-64-XXXX_sw-network`. After many worktrees, Docker runs out of IP addresses.\
n\nThe fix could be to either:\n1. Use an external network that\'s shared across
all worktrees\n2. Add network cleanup to the E2E teardown\n3. Use `docker compos
e down --remove-orphans` with explicit network removal\n\nLooking at `run-e2e.sh
`, the CI mode has:\n```bash\ncleanup() {\n  echo "🧹 清理 E2E 环境..."\n  cd "$
PROJECT_ROOT"\n  make e2e-env-down 2>/dev/null || true\n}\n```\n\nAnd `make e2e-
env-down` runs `docker compose down`. But `docker compose down` removes the cont
